Paul,<br><br>
You do pose some rather interesting questions.<br><br>
&quot;I think (sometimes informative other times out of frustration) that humans like the rest of the animals on earth are simply territorial. We protect, for whatever reason our continuance, to maintain our ___.&quot;<br><br>
I am sure that your study of genetically deficient animals has little to do with mature Homo sapiens.  The responses of a civilized nation could be reduced to territorial battles, but they are almost always economically or ideologically based. Assume for a moment that we are the superior species because we have the capacity for logic and understanding.<br><br>
History has proven that man fights wars for complex reasons.  It can not be reduced to one simple formula.  You will find that animals fight only for the right of survival and then only for the hierarchy of the predators and herbivores.  Everything is a victim of another.<br><br>
Man is a much more cunning animal.  Wars are driven by complex desires.  It rarely is based on basic survival or boundaries.  When boundaries are defined and rules put in place they will be defended.  Man is the only animal that will kill for the pleasure.  Civilized societies don't.<br>

